For Github
echo "# sql_llm" >> README.md
git init
git add README.md
git commit -m "first commit"
git branch -M main
git remote add origin git@github.com:alikhanzadi/sql_llm.git
git push -u origin main

# Untrack a file (removing it from git history - when you added a file but later decide not to include it and want to remove it)
git rm --cached .env

#Remove Git completely
rm -rf .git 

Git STATUS



SSH --------------------------------------------------------------------
1. Check for existing SSH
ls -al ~/.ssh
2. Generate a new SSH key 
ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -C "khanzadi.ali@gmail.com"
    Enter file in which to save the key (/Users/alikhanzadi/.ssh/id_ed25519): github
    Enter passphrase for "github" (empty for no passphrase): 
    Enter same passphrase again: 
    Your identification has been saved in github
    Your public key has been saved in github.pub
    The key fingerprint is:

3. Add the SSH key to your GitHub account 
pbcopy < ~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub #copy the text, the entire thing.
Go to GitHub: Navigate to GitHub SSH Settings.
Add New Key: Click New SSH key, give it a title (e.g., "Ali's MacBook Pro"), and paste the key into the "Key" field.
Save: Click Add SSH key.
Make sure the keys (pub + the other ones) are placed in ~/.ssh

4. Verify and Push
ssh -T git@github.com
You should see: "Hi [YourUsername]! You've successfully authenticated..." 

